{{italic title}} {{Infobox Painting | image_file= The_Frame_(Frida_Kahlo_painting).jpg | alt= | image_size= | title=The Frame | other_language_1= | other_title_1= | artist=[[Frida Kahlo]] | year=1938 | type=[[Oil painting|Oil]] on [[glass]] | height_metric= | width_metric= | city=Paris | museum=[[Musée National d'Art Moderne]] }} '''''The Frame''''' is a 1938 self-portrait by [[Frida Kahlo]].<ref>[https://www.fridakahlo.org/self-portrait-the-frame.jsp ]</ref> The painting is notable as the first work by a 20th-century Mexican artist to be purchased by a major international museum, when it was acquired by [[The Louvre]] in 1939. The painting is now shown at the [[Musée National d'Art Moderne]] in the [[Centre Pompidou]] in Paris.<ref>http://www.fridakahlofans.com/c0255.html</ref>
It was the only sale Kahlo made in her Paris exhibition.<ref>Terri Hardin ''Frida Kahlo: A Modern Master'' 2005- Page 68 1597640891 "Breton annoyed Kahlo by exhibiting a jumble of various folk objects of varying artistic merit that he had acquired in Mexico — "junk," as she called it. Nevertheless, the objects were no doubt sufficiently exotic to the European sensibility, and Breton's instincts were probably right in presenting them. While the exhibit was not a financial success (due to the imminent onset of World War II), the Louvre chose to purchase one of Kahlo's works, ''The Frame'' (c. 1938). ''The Frame'' is a lively work ...</ref>
